-- French Stocks: Renault, ArcelorMittal, Veolia, Vilmorin Move
-- B y   D a v i d   A l t a n e r
-- 2010-10-07T15:48:40Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-07/ldc-renault-seloger-total-and-vilmorin-may-move-french-equity-preview.html
France’s  CAC 40 Index  rose 5.56, or
0.2 percent, to 3,770.47 at the 5:30 p.m. close in Paris, a
third day of gains. The SBF-120 Index increased 0.1 percent to
2,809.79.  The following shares rose or fell in the French capital.
Stock symbols are in parentheses.  ArcelorMittal SA  (MT NA) increased 1.1 percent to 24.43
euros. The world’s biggest steelmaker had an antitrust fine cut
by about 50 million euros ($69.8 million) after the European
Union corrected a mistake in the way it punished companies over
a cartel in pre-stressing steel.  Edenred  (EDEN FP) lost 1.4 percent to 14.94 euros after
France’s strategic investment fund, Le Fonds Strategique
d’Investisement, sold 6.8 percent of the company at 14.70 euros
a share. FSI no longer holds any Edenred stock, it said in an e-
mailed statement.  GDF Suez SA  (GSZ FP) rose 2.1 percent to 26.84 euros. GDF
and Belgonucleaire signed an agreement with China National
Nuclear Corp. to construct a test plant for making nuclear fuel
for Chinese reactors.  Renault SA  (RNO FP) surged 8.5 percent to 39.60 euros, the
biggest gain since August 2009. The carmaker sold its 14.9
percent stake in truckmaker Volvo AB for 3 billion euros, the
company said in a statement. Renault sold the 302.9 million
Class B shares in a private placement. It did not identify who
bought the stock.  Veolia Environnement SA  (VIE FP) gained 2.5 percent to
19.80 euros. The world’s biggest water utility was raised to
“buy” from “neutral” at UBS AG. The brokerage said that
Veolia has stabilized operationally and now presents “a
reasonably attractive valuation case.”  Vilmorin & Cie.  (RIN FP) fell 5.4 percent to 75.50 euros,
its largest decline since February. The seed company said full-
year net income rose to 54.2 million euros from 53 million euros
a year earlier. Analysts had forecast profit of 63.8 million
euros, according to the average of three estimates compiled by
Bloomberg.  To contact the reporter on this story:
David Altaner in London at 
 daltaner@bloomberg.net  